€”â€Šsecure and isolated environments within a processor where data and code are encrypted and protected. Hereâ€™s how it works step byÂ step:</p><p><strong>1. Setting Up the Trusted Execution Environment (TEE)</strong><br>A TEE is a secure enclave within a processor. It isolates the execution of sensitive code and data from the rest of the system, ensuring confidentiality and integrity. Only authorized code can access the data inside theÂ TEE.</p><p>For example, modern processors from Intel (SGX), AMD (SEV), and ARM (TrustZone) offer built-in TEEs to enable Confidential Computing.</p><p><strong>2. Data Encryption During Processing</strong><br>i. Before Processing: Data is encrypted and transferred to the cloud or local environment.</p><p>ii. During Processing: The encrypted data is loaded into the TEE. Inside the enclave, the data is decrypted and processed securely. This ensures that even the operating system, hypervisor, or cloud provider canâ€™t access theÂ data.</p><p>iii. After Processing: Once computation is complete, the data is re-encrypted and sentÂ back.</p><p><strong>3. Attestation Mechanism</strong><br>To build trust, TEEs provide an attestation feature.</p><p>This is a cryptographic proof that the TEE is configured correctly and hasnâ€™t been tampered with.<br>It assures users and applications that the data and code running inside the TEE areÂ secure.</p><p><strong>4. Isolation from Host Environment</strong><br>The TEE operates independently from the host operating system, ensuring that even if the OS is compromised, the data inside the TEE remainsÂ secure.</p><p><strong>5. Integration with Cloud Platforms</strong><br>Major cloud providers like AWS, Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud have adopted Confidential Computing frameworks to support secure workloads:</p><p>i. Azure Confidential Computing: Provides support for secure enclaves on virtual machines using Intel SGX and AMDÂ SEV.</p><p>ii. Google Cloud Confidential VMs: Encrypts data in use without requiring any changes to your applications.</p><p>iii. AWS Nitro Enclaves: Offers isolated compute environments for processing highly sensitive data.</p><p><strong>Key Benefits of Confidential Computing</strong><br><strong>1. Data-In-Use Protection</strong><br>By keeping data encrypted during computation, Confidential Computing eliminates vulnerabilities during processing.</p><p><strong>2. Compliance and Privacy</strong><br>Industries dealing with sensitive data can meet strict regulatory requirements, such as GDPR, HIPAA, andÂ CCPA.</p><p><strong>3. Collaborative Computing</strong><br>Organizations can securely collaborate on shared datasets without exposing sensitive information to each other or thirdÂ parties.</p><p><strong>4. Reduced Insider Threats</strong><br>Even administrators or insiders with high-level access canâ€™t view or tamper with the data processed withinÂ TEEs.</p><p>#ConfidentialComputing #CyberSecurity #CloudSecurity #TrustedExecutionEnvironments #DataSecurity</p><img src=\"https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=527d5ed7de43\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" alt=\"\">","pubDate":"Mon, 16 Dec 2024 05:36:50 GMT","link":"https://cyberwithatharva.medium.com/what-is-confidential-computing-and-how-does-it-work-527d5ed7de43?source=rss-13884e62d697------2","guid":"https://medium.com/p/527d5ed7de43"},{"title":"Zero Trust Architecture in Multi-Cloud Environments: Building a Secure Future","content":"<figure><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*poVyEBuWk_ngZdXQFpCY9A.jpeg\" /><figcaption>Zero Trust Architecture</figcaption></figure><p>The rise of multi-cloud environments has transformed how organizations approach their IT infrastructure. But, with great flexibility comes an equally great challenge about maintaining robust security across all these platforms. That is where Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA) comes into play. It is a security framework that operates on the principle of â€œnever trust, alway